# Model routing (required first step)

Before implementing or drafting client material: **classify the task** and **pick a model**. Full guide: `agents/MODEL-ROUTING.md`.

## Models

| Model | Use when |
| ----- | -------- |
| **Composer 2** | Fast repo work: edits, scripts, git, clear-scope implementation |
| **GPT-5.5** | Balanced mixed work: research, PM updates, code + light prose |
| **GPT-5.3 Codex** | Deep code: app stack, tooling, refactors, debug after one failed fix |
| **Sonnet 4.6** | Client copy, narratives, long docs, Google Docs/MCP, style guides |
| **Opus 4.7** | Hard judgment: scope ambiguity, strategy, stuck twice, high-stakes compliance |

Optimize for **task fit**, not default speed.

## Quick route

| Task | Model |
| ---- | ----- |
| Code / CI | Composer 2 → Codex 5.3 if stuck |
| Client-facing copy | Sonnet 4.6 → Opus 4.7 if high stakes |
| Google Docs / doc MCP | Sonnet 4.6 |
| PM / scope | GPT-5.5 → Opus 4.7 if ambiguous |
| Trivial fix | Composer 2 |

Escalate once if client-readable claims matter or the same fix failed twice.

Do not use the fastest model for every task. If the user pinned a model, follow it unless they ask for a recommendation.

When saving Calyx reasoning or ADRs, copy **model** / **tier** / **escalation** into the optional **Agent context** section if you stated them in the thread.
